Started 2022 with COVID, but it taught me the very important lesson about these tests - even a faint line means positive. 

This revelation would prove particularly helpful when 6 months later we learned we were expecting our first child. And then two months later when we learned we were expecting our first TWO children. 🪺

Another miraculous lesson in surrender, wonder and the healing power of love. 💐💐

It turns out your ovaries are more likely to drop 2+ eggs on one cycle as you age. Especially for women in their mid-30s and early-40s. Did you know this? I did not. Another reason I’ve spent my career advocating for more comprehensive education around women’s bodies. 

The word and energy I’m calling in 2023 is “in wonder” and “wonderous.” I’ve been truly astounded by the power of surrender and hope. For Alex, it’s new beginnings. With big big love. -CS

I did not know my heart could live outside my body. We’re so happy to introduce you to the twins: Farrell Arthur-Stiller and Ronan Arthur-Stiller. But you can call them Rellie and Ronie. They made their grand entrance a little earlier than planned on January 9, 2023. Our hearts are so full. 🧡🤰🏼🌿🥹
First time leaving the house with the twins on my own 🙌 … and a couple other cute moments that came before.

What a triple threat! 🔥 One of my favorite topics: #pelvicfloor therapy, written by one of my favorite health writers @daniellefriedmanwrites spotlighting one of my favorite clients @theoriginway

This is the second @nytimes piece for my consulting agency in four months. Love to see it. 🏆 Now, back to mat leave and off to see my pelvic floor therapist.

It’s always a pleasure …

To see a piece you collab’d on take off for @nytimes across digital on email, on Facebook and on the website. 

🙌 for more people learning about pelvic floor therapy. Congrats @theoriginway & @daniellefriedmanwrites

After tearing up the charts on digital for the @nytimes last week (#1 on email, top #5 on website and Facebook) it’s wonderful to see @theoriginway piece make the print edition this week.

Such a pleasure to not only help place the companies I work with in leading outlets, but also see the pieces they’re featured in really take off and offer solid public service journalism. 

Congrats @theoriginway and @daniellefriedmanwrites 

PS: My other maternity leave win? Seeing Magic Mike: Last Dance twice in theaters in 10 days. #AMA 😉

We failed Austin Lyle. We failed Austin Lyle like we fail so many men, and in particular men of color.

I didn’t know Austin at all except he worked at my local UPS store and made such an impression on me on my near weekly trips there.

Even to a stranger, Austin was clearly a kind and gentle soul. In a busy harried store he was always so helpful, on top of it, kind. As I said, his gentle and grounded presence made an impression on me. 

According to media reports, Austin brought a gun to his school in Denver that resulted in a shooting. According to media reports, he then took his own life. 

According to media reports, the story here is about gun reform and a young troubled kid. I would like to offer a different perspective - What was clear to even a stranger was that Austin did not fit within “the man box” we expect men and young men to fit in. What could be different if instead of ostracitzing and punishing Austin had he been helped, offered counseling and been shown that he too belonged and was special. 

Putting the pieces of this story together was so jarring for me as I realized this was the same special young man from my weekly local routine. 

We failed Austin and I feel deep sorrow for that and for all men who feel cast out. This echos sentiments I heard from men in  my reporting of Modern Manhood. 

#austinlyle here (I am borrowing this photo from a community post on Facebook.)

My first book Modern Manhood has recently been cited in three different publications and in two different languages (including the new book Staff Matters. Congrats @bonnielowkramen 🙌) Always a joy to see good work travel effortlessly far and wide.

Four months with the Arthur-Stiller boys. I’ll tell ya, Alex and I have surprised ourselves by finding parenthood to be one of the most grounding and purposeful experiences. Dare I say, calming. Very grateful for these little rug rats and hope you get to meet them soon. 🫶
As @v_solesmith says, “I would happily trade brunch for paid family leave, reproductive rights and some gun control laws.” But I will also take brunch and a moment to celebrate my first #mothersday
I said, “Let’s take a family photo for Mother’s Day.” And little Josphine, our first born, said not without me 😺 Happy #mothersday from the Arthur-Stiller’s.
Dads Dadding. My mom tells me it’s wonderful and hopeful to see how involved, loving, attentive and intuitive our generation of Dad’s are dadding and I have to agree. 💐

Took our sons to #pride. We feel it’s important to teach them early about celebrating and loving everyone exactly for who they are, as they are - and to recommit every year to fight for those who are not, yet. 

Two years ago I was at a Pride event that made me wonder if we were coming to a time in my lifetime that Pride month wouldn’t feel so urgent. It seemed, at the time, we were moving in that direction for #lgbtqia rights. And wow, what a sorrowful backslide we have seen the last two years. 

More important than ever to reaffirm our commitment to fighting for love, kindness and Justice.
Family photos. 😜

Today marks the end of my 6.5 month journey of breastfeeding, nursing and pumping for our twins. I’ve thought a lot about this experience and wanted to share some reflections.

The pressure to breastfeed in the US is cultish and the absolute height of hypocrisy given the current culture and system we live in.

The World Health Organization recommends breastfeeding to some extent for 12 months, yet we have no federally mandated parental leave policy. I live in a state that at this exact moment has no law requiring companies to offer maternity leave at all. At all. Shocking. Inhumane. 

Some insurance policies (s/o to #Anthem) don’t cover lactation consultants and if you’ve ever breastfed you know you’re one of the lucky ones if it comes easily to you and you don’t need outside help.

The pressure to nurse ties mama to baby, or babies. Then the pressure to get back to work pressures moms to pump and while there are laws in place about allowing women time to pump, every mom I spoke to explained pumping + working is nearly impossible.

Further, the #medtech technology of breast pumps in 2023 is offensive. You’re telling me my dishwasher can be synced up to my phone and I can order groceries by voice memo, but the equipment given to women across this country to feed their newborns is so finicky that if you bend halfway over, it falls out? Offensive. 

Story time - one day when the twins were 5 months old, we had a babysitter for the day so I could go out and run errands. For hours, I *completely* forgot to pump or go home to nurse. I was free! Living my life! And then it hit me *gasp!* I had forgotten my duties, guilt creeped in. And you know what I thought to myself? Controversial take though it may be, “Breastfeeding as has been presented to me is anti-feminist.” 

We don’t live in a society that adequately supports people to breastfeed and yet the pressure to do so is so immense. 

I have to publicly call out this impossible contradiction because I felt so woefully unprepared and taken aback by this experience, I just can’t sit by. 

I’m proud of the effort I put in and you know what? I’m thrilled to be done. Do better America. 

#breastfeeding #nursing

This week @pewresearch released a fascinating report that revealed 79% of women married to men in the US took their husbands last name. 

The report further indicated that of straight women unyet married, 33% planned to take their husbands name, 23% would keep their own and a brave 17% would hyphenate (I joked a lot about this in my stories since I was saddled with a hypenated last name growing up - hated it. But then inexplicably saddled both my kids with one as well.)

This report is so topical. I have spent so much time thinking about who should get whose last name and why. There really is no win-win situation in the current system I feel, especially when children are involved. I LOVE hearing about peoples’ creative workarounds in this imperfect system. 

As is often the case, ya’ll had a lot to say about this in the DMs. Here are some of the highlights.

(Apologies for the less than desirable presentation, there’s no great way to share stories on the main and these were too good not to share.)

This is our proudly Jewish-blended family with dear ones on both sides of the conflict and a call for peace.

Jews make up a smaller percentage of the population than many realize. Most sources put the global Jewish population at 16 million. To put that into pop culture context, Kim Kardashian has 22x more followers on Instagram than there are Jews living worldwide.

For that reason, an attack on Jews ripples from the head to the toe of our global community in a heartbeat. 

I share that information with non-Jews in the hope of explaining why attacks are felt so profoundly & as anyone who has felt truly othered may understand. 

And still, calls to stand with Israel are not compelling to our family. I would never&will never pledge my loyalty to a state. Stateheads do not represent the collective best interest as is laid bare in the horrific events unfolding right now. 

Here is who I will fight like hell for - mothers having their babies ripped from their arms, women whose bodily autonomy is sacrificed as a bargaining chip in wars they didn’t ask for, young people who deserve to grow up freely and safely. I care not what God you pray to nor what country issues your passport.

I will fight like hell for anyone who is living with a boot on their neck. Horrifically, this happens everywhere from right outside my doorstep to half way across the world. 

A thought I cannot get over: according to reports, two weeks ago 2,000 Israeli& Palestinian women gathered in a show of solidarity and to demand that women be given a seat at the negotiating table - these women are fighting for peace.

Put women at the table who speak the universal language of living in a world not made for us; put women at the table who would never rip a child from another woman’s arms knowing she could never perpetrate that kind of violence from mother to mother; put women at the table who would never trap another family as bombs are dropped on their homes with borders blocked; put women at the table who would never see another woman raped. 

Put women at the table. 

Our hearts break for each dear, sweet, beloved human life at risk. Where is our humanity?

 @womenwagepeace @women.of.the.sun_

A beautiful thing happens when you become friends with people from different countries than you, of different races than you, of different religions than you.

Their families become your families. Their babies become your babies. And when they need you, you fight like hell for them.

It’s important to Alex and me to teach our young 9-month old boys, who will grow up with such immense privilege, that often we will be showing up shoulder to shoulder with people who look nothing like us as I did when I marched for Black Lives Matter, to abolish ICE, against President Trump’s immigration ban, for reproductive rights and in both Women’s Marches (all featured here.)

To our Palestinian friends - We see you. We love you. We are with you. 

To our Jewish friends - We love you. And we hope you can turn into your hearts and see that our people more than most know militarized and systemic murder of innocent women, men and children is always wrong. We must urge for an immediate ceasefire.

In our proudly Jewish family, this is not a controversial stance. This is righteous and good. And this urgent. Please call your reps, donate and march. #ceasefire

The twins’ first Thanksgiving at daycare. 

Something I think about a lot - Alex and I are considered “older parents" and for my personal journey I feel grateful for that. In my 20s, I wouldn't have been interested in Thanksgiving parties at daycare. 

But these days, it's the absolute highlight of my week. 

And the gratitude does not pass me by that I wasn't given this experience until I was ready to receive it.

I want to draw an important through line for you and I hope this travels far and wide - do not look to the entertainment industries (film, television and music) for a moral compass: 

🚨Actresses @susansarandon @melissabarreram and many more are dropped by their reps for speaking out in support of Palestine. 

🚨The music industry is finally having its #metoo movement 

🚨Hollywood for decades protected Harvey Weinstein and others above the safety of many innocent survivors. 

As someone who has reported on the impacts of these industries on the lives of every day folks, I want to be extremely clear: these industries have long shown us they will protect people in power to the detriment of people without power.

Ask @deardrewdixon Ask @kkbutter Ask so, so many others. 

The reason I am highlighting this is because I don’t want you to read about people in the entertainment industry speaking out and getting “blacklisted” and have you be surprised or even worse - discouraged. 

Horribly, these 🚨cannot surprise us. But the beauty of this time is seeing real people in multitudes stand up and take a stand - and often now, justice is delivered. Even if it is too hard fought and delivered too late - it is delivered.

Keep speaking up, friends. Keep standing up for what is right. We are with you. 🕊️

(And for those who don’t know me personally, I’m speaking as a concerned citizen with a decade in public service journalism and a Jewish American.)

Meet Editor-in-Chief of @thedoe, Cleo Stiller:

“I come to The Doe after a decade of working in public service journalism as an Emmy Award and Peabody Award-nominated television journalist and author. The throughline on all my projects — from my television show about health and technology on Fusion to my book about men after the #MeToo movement with Simon & Schuster to my years of working with mission-aligned brands funded by Alexis Ohanian, Chelsea Clinton and more — is always this: people first, humanity first, empathy first.

That’s why I’m so proud of the work we do at The Doe where we showcase personal, anonymous stories to promote empathy and change the way people relate to each other on the internet. Connection and understanding are the building blocks to a more compassionate world and we surely need more of that.”

Reviving The Doe after a ten-month hiatus, Cleo Stiller has masterfully breathed new life into the publication, with her first week of leadership seeing thousands engage, hundreds comment, and numerous organic story pitches. Her diverse background as an activist, journalist, author, and content creator has been pivotal in this resurgence, redefining The Doe as a pivotal space for authentic, empathetic, and community-centric storytelling. Under Cleo’s stewardship, The Doe challenges readers to confront their biases, humanizes major news stories, and provokes thoughtful introspection, effectively transforming the way we interact with news and each other. Establishing itself as the premier destination for anonymous publishing online, The Doe stands out as a beacon for those seeking to share their stories with the world in a safe and impactful way.

UNPRECEDENTED — a bloody collage. 
United Nations: “Unprecedented and unparalleled civilian death toll.” 
Save the Children: “The conditions in Gaza are unprecedented and have rendered our jobs impossible.”
UNICEF: “Gaza has become a graveyard for thousands of children... from the earliest days of the unprecedented hostilities in the Gaza Strip.”
Human Rights Watch: “Unprecedented repression demands unprecedented response.”

I want to talk about the word “UNPRECEDENTED.” Such a powerful word meaning, “never done or known before.” Experts will use this word sparingly and when they do, we must take notice.

As someone who has made a career out of talking to experts in their fields, my attention — not only as a journalist but as a person (and a Jewish one at that) who cares deeply about other people — has come to almost a complete stop with all eyes on Pal3stin3. “Unprecedented” I have seen uttered over and over again. 

According to the prominent NGO Save the Children, “More children have been killed in Gaza in three weeks than in all global conflicts annually since 2019.” According to the U.N. 160 children Gaza die every day.

United Nations, UNICEF, Doctors Without Borders, Save the Children, Human Rights Watch. People have told me they are nervous to find their voice in this time. Take courage in knowing that to side with these NGOs doing God’s work is not a controversial nor a political move. If they say this time is unprecedented, how can you turn away?

From our Jewish family to yours, I want to remind you that American citizens have an oversized impact on the global stage. Make your voice heard. 

If you need some help making the calls to your reps, DM me. I am happy and honored to be in this with you.

It’s a high stakes venture to go from not even trying to, “Oh maybe we’ll have one girl,” to “Oh my gosh - twin boys!!” But I have personally found the experience of motherhood to be the most purposeful and grounding. I’ve had a long habit in my life of setting high goals, achieving them, feeling discontent and unmoored. And while I can’t lie - we are so bone tired after this year - but I am also very, very peaceful. Happy first birthday to my little loves Farrell and Ronan and my big love Alex.
